description:
The Art of Oscar Wilde
Princeton University Press | 1967 | ISBN: N/A | English | 256 pages | PDF | 31.4 MB

The art and life of Oscar Wilde presents the kind of absurd and inverted paradox for which Wilde the epigrammist was justly admired. A vocal devotee of Art for Art's Sake, he led a life so dedicated to his aesthetic principles that he eventually paid the price of his commitment. While posing as a sensualist desiring only to "drift with every passion," he produced works dominated by a horror of corruption and a pathetic yearning for lost innocence
